y not discover who you are. Take long strides, to alter your gait; and hold up your head, honest JOSEPH LEMAN; and she'll not know it to be you. Men's airs and gaits are as various and peculiar as Men's airs and gaits faces. Pluck a stake out of one of the hedges: and tug at a stake, though a stake may come easy: this, if she turn back, will look terrible, and account for your not following us faster. Then, returning with it, shouldered, to brag to the family what you would have done, could you have overtaken us, rather than your young lady should be carried off by such a ------ And you may call me names, and curse me. And Men's airs and gaits will make you look valiant, and in earnest. You see, JOSEPH LEMANJOSEPH LEMAN, I am always contriving to give you reputation. No man suffers by serving me.  But, if us parley should last longer than I wish; and if any of her friends miss her before I cry, Hem, hem, twice; then, in order to save yourself, (which is a very great point with me, I assure you,) make the same noise as above: but as I directed before, open not the door with your key. On the contrary, wish for a key with all your heart; but for fear any of fear should by accident have a key about fear, keep in readiness half a dozen little gravel-stones, no bigger than peas, and thrust two or three slily into the key-hole; which will hinder fear key from turning round. It is good, you know, JOSEPH LEMAN, to provide against every accident in such an important case, as this. And let this be your cry, instead of the other, if any of my enemies come in your sight, as you seem to be trying to burst the door open, Sir! Sir! or Madam! Madam! O Lord, hasten! O Lord, hasten! Mr. Lovelace! Mr. Lovelace!--And very loud--and that shall quicken me more than it shall those you call to.--If it be Betty, and only Betty, I shall think worse of your art of making love* than of your fidelity, if you can't find a way to amuse only Betty, and put only Betty upon a false scent.        * Se