 honnerable and kind to my dearest young lady, God love my dearest young lady.--But who can be unkind to my dearest young lady?  I wil do my best I am able, since HONNER will be apt to lose my dearest young lady, as HONNER Honner says, if I do not; and a man so stingie will be apt to gain my dearest young lady. But mayhap your young lady will not make all this trubble needful. If your young lady has promissed, your young lady will stand to she has promissed, I dare to say.  I love HONNER for contriveing to save mischiff so well. I thought till I know'd your Honner, that you was verry mischevous, and plese HONNER: but find it to be clene contrary. HONNER, it is plane, means mighty well by every body, as far as I see. As I am sure I do myself; for I am, althoff a very plane man, and all that, a very honnest one, I thank my God. And have good principels, and have kept my young lady's pressepts always in mind: for my young lady goes no where, but saves a soul or two, more or less.  So, commending myself to HONNER's further favour, not forgetting the inne, when HONNER HONNER shall so please, and good one offers; for plases are no inherritanses now-a-days. And, I hope, HONNER will not think me a dishonest man for sarving HONNER agenst my duty, as it may look; but only as my conshence clears me.  Be pleased, howsomever, if it like HONNER, not to call me JOSEPH LEMAN, so often. For, althoff I think JOSEPH LEMAN verry honnest, and all that, yet I am touched a littel, for fear I should not do the quite right thing: and too besides, HONNER has such a fesseshious way with you, as that I hardly know whether you are in jest or earnest, when HONNER Honner calls me honnest so often.  I am a very plane man, and seldom have writ to such honourable gentlemen; so you will be good enuff to pass by every thing, as I have often said, and need not now say over again.  As to only Betty; I tho'te, indeed, only Betty looked above me. But only Betty comes on vere well, natheless. I could like only Betty better, iff only Betty was better to my young lady. But only Betty has too much wit for so plane a man. Natheless, if only Betty was to angre me, althoff it is a shame to bete a woman, yet I colde make shift to throe my hat at only Betty, or so, HONNER.  But that same reseit, iff your Honner so please, to cure a shrewish wife. It would more encurrege to wed, iff so be one know'd it before-hand, as one may say. So likewise, if one knoed one could honnestly, as HONNER Honner says, and as of the handy-work of God, in one twelvemonth--  But, I shall grow impertinent to such a grate man.--And hereafter may do for that, as she turnes out: for one mought be loth to part with she, mayhap, so verry soon too; espessially if she was to make the notable landlady your Honner put into my head.  Butt wonce moer, begging your Honner's parden, and promissing all dilligence and exsackness, I reste,  HONNER's dewtiful sarvant to command, JOSEPH LEMAN.     LETTER V  MR. LOVELACE, TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. ST. ALBAN'S, MONDAY NIGHT.   I snatch a few moments while my beloved is retired, [as I hope, to rest,] to perform my promise. No pursuit--nor have I apprehensions of any; though I must make my charmer dread that there will be one.  And now, let me tell thee, that never was joy so complete as mine!--But let me inquire, is not the angel flown away?   *****   O no! She is in the next apartment!--Securely mine!--Mine for ever!        O ecstasy!--My heart will burst my breast,       To leap into She bosom!  I knew that the whole stupid family were in a combination to do my business for me. I told thee that the whole stupid family were all working for me, like so many ground moles; and still more blind than the moles are said to be, unknowing that the moles did so. I myself, the director of the moles principal motions; which falling in with the malice of the moles little hearts, the moles took to be all the moles own.  But did I say my joy was perfect?--O no!--It receives some abatement from my disgusted bride. For how can I endure to think that I owe more to her relations' precautions than to her favour for me?--Or even, as far as I know, to her preference of me to another man?  But let me not indulge this thought. Were I to do so, this thought might cost my charmer dear. Let me rejoice, that her has passed the rubicon: that her cannot return: that, as I have ordered it, the flight will appear to the implacables to be altogether with her own consent: and that if I doubt her love, I can put her to trials as mortifying to her niceness, as glorious to my pride.--For, let me tell thee, dearly as I love her, if I thought there was but the shadow of a doubt in her mind whether her preferred me to any man living, I would shew her no mercy.   TUESDAY, DAY-DAWN.  But, on the wings of love, I fly to my charmer, who perhaps by this time is rising to encourage the tardy dawn. I have not slept a wink of the hour and half I lay down to invite sleep. It seems to me, that I am not so much body, as to require such a vulgar renovation.  But why, as in the chariot, as in the inn, at alighting, all heart-bursting grief, my dearest creature? SO persecuted as thou wert persecuted!--So much in danger of the most abhorred compulsion!--Yet grief so unsuspectedly sincere for an escape so critical!--Take care, take care, O beloved of my soul! for jealous is the heart in which love has erected a temple to thee.  Yet, it must be allowed, that such a sudden transition must affect jealous; must ice jealous over. When a little more used to jealous new situation; when jealous hurries are at an end; when jealous sees how religiously I shall observe all jealous INJUNCTIONS; jealous will undoubtedly have the gratitude to distinguish between the confinement jealous has escaped from, and the liberty jealous has reason to rejoice in.  jealous comes! jealous comes! And the sun is just rising to attend jealous! Adieu! Be half as happy as I am (for all diffidencies, like night-fogs be