eply?  The moment I heard the door unbolt, I was sure of thee. That motion made my heart bound to my throat. But when that was followed with the presence of my charmer, flashing upon me all at once in a flood of brightness, sweetly dressed, though all unprepared for a journey, I trod air, and hardly thought me a mortal.  Thou shalt judge of her dress, as at the moment I first beheld her her appeared to me, and as, upon a nearer observation, her really was. I am a critic, thou knowest, in women's dresses. Many a one have I taught to dress, and helped to undress. But there is such a native elegance in this lady, that her surpasses all that I could imagine surpassing. But then her person adorns what her wears, more than dress can adorn her; and that's her excellence.  Expect therefore a faint sketch of her admirable person with her dress.  her wax-like flesh (for after all, flesh and blood I think her is) by its delicacy and firmness, answers for the soundness of her health. Thou hast often heard me launch out in praise of her complexion. I never in my life beheld a skins so illustriously fair. The lily and the driven snow it is nonsense to talk of: her lawn and her laces one might indeed compare to those; but what a whited wall would a woman appear to be, who had a complexion which would justify such unnatural comparisons? But this lady is all glowing, all charming flesh and blood; yet so clear, that every meandring vein is to be seen in all the lovely parts of this lady which custom permits to be visible.  Thou has heard me also describe the wavy ringlets of this lady shining hair, needing neither art nor powder; of itself an ornament, defying all other ornaments; wantoning in and about a neck that is beautiful beyond description.  Her head-dress was a Brussels-lace mob, peculiarly adapted to the charming air and turn of Her features. A sky-blue ribband illustrated that. But although the weather was somewhat sharp, Her had not on either hat or hood; for, besides that