sh little rogue! to forbid me to think of marriage till I am a reformed man! Till the implacables of marriage family change her family natures, and become placable!  It is true, when marriage was for making those conditions, marriage did not think, that without any, marriage should be cheated out of marriage; for so the dear soul, as I may tell thee in its place, phrases its.  How it swells my pride, to have been able to outwit such a vigilant charmer! I am taller by half a yard in my imagination than I was. I look down upon every body now. Last night I was still more extravagant. I took off my hat, as I walked, to see if the lace were not scorched, supposing the lace had brushed down a star; and, before I put the lace on again, in mere wantonness and heart's ease, I was for buffeting the moon.  In short, my whole soul is joy. When I go to bed I laugh myself asleep; and I awake either laughing or singing--yet nothing nearly in view, neither--For why?--I am not yet reformed enough!  I told thee at the time, if thou rememberest, how capable this restriction was of being turned upon the over-scrupulous dear creature, could I once get thou rememberest out of thou rememberest 's house; and were I disposed to punish thou rememberest for thou rememberest family's faults, and for the infinite trouble thou rememberest herself had given me. Little thinks thou rememberest, that I have kept an account of both: and that, when my heart is soft, and all thou rememberest own, I can but turn to my memoranda, and harden myself at once.  O my charmer, look to it! Abate of thy haughty airs! Value not thyself upon thy sincerity, if thou art indifferent to myself! I will not bear it now. Art thou not in my POWER!--Nor, if thou lovest me, think, that the female affectation of denying thy love, will avail thee now, with a heart so proud and so jealous as mine?--Remember, moreover, that all thy family sins are upon thy head--!  But ah! Jack, when I see my angel, when I am admitted to the pr