f diminish? That her will take care of her; and, since her friends thing it not worth while to pursue her, her will be left to her own care? That I shall make Mrs. Sorlings's house more agreeable by my absence?--And go to Berks, to town, or wherever I will,' [to the devil, I suppose,] 'with all her heart?'  The impolitic charmer!--To a temper so vindictive as her thins mine! To a free-liver, as her believes me to be, who has her in his power! I was before, as thou knowest, balancing; now this scale, now that, the heaviest. I only waited to see how her will would work, how her would lead me on. Thou seest what bias here takes--And wilt thou doubt that her will be determined by it? Were not her faults, before this, numerous enough? Why will her put me upon looking back?  I will sit down to argue with myself by-and-by, and thou shalt be acquainted with the result.  If thou didst but know, if thou hadst but beheld, what an abject slave her made me look like!--I had given myself high airs, as her called thou didst but know: but thou didst but know were airs that shewed my love for her: that shewed I could not live out of her company. But her took me down with a vengeance! her made me look about myself. So much advantage had her over myself; such severe turns upon myself; by my soul, Jack, I had hardly a word to say for myself. I am ashamed to tell thee what a poor creature her made me look like! But I could have told her something that would have humbled her pretty pride at the instant, had her been in a proper place, and proper company about her.  To such a place then--and where her cannot fly me--And then to see how my will works, and what can be done with the amorous see-saw; now humble, now proud; now expecting, or demanding; now submitting, or acquiescing--till I have tried resistance.  But these hints are at present enough. I may further explain myself as I go along; and as I confirm or recede in my future motions. If her will revive past disobligations! If her will--But no more, no more, as I said, at present, of threatenings.     LETTER XVII  MR. Mr. Lovelace. [IN CONTINUATION.]   And do I not see that I shall need nothing but patience, in order to have all power with me? For what shall we say, if all these complaints of a character wounded; these declarations of increasing regrets for meeting me; of resentments never to be got over for my seducing her away; these angry commands to leaver her:--What shall we say, if all were to mean nothing but MATRIMONY? And what if my forbearing to enter upon that subject come out to be the true cause of my forbearing to enter upon that subject petulance and uneasiness!  I had once before played about the skirts of the irrevocable obligation; but thought myself obliged to speak in clouds, and to run away from that subject, as soon as her took my meaning, lest her should imagine my meaning to be ungenerously urged, now her was in some sort in my power, as her had forbid me beforehand, to touch upon my meaning, till I were in a state of visible reformation, and till a reconciliation with her friends were probable. But now, out-argued, out-talented, and pushed so vehemently to leave one of whom I had no good pretence to hold, if her would go; and who could so easily, if I had given her cause to doubt, have thrown her into other protection, or have returned to Harlowe-place and Solmes; I spoke out upon that subject, and offered reasons, although with infinite doubt and hesitation, [lest her should be offended at me, Belford!] why her should assent to the legal tie, and make me the happiest of men. And O how the mantle cheek, the downcast eye, the silent yet trembling lip, and the heaving bosom, a sweet collection of heightened beauties, gave evidence that the tender was not mortally offensive!  Charming creature! thought I, [but I charge thee, that thou let not any of the sex know my exultation,*] Is it so soon come to this? Am I already lord of the destiny of a Clarissa Harlowe? Am I already