ther dearly notwithstanding. If my mother had not me to find fault with, my mother must find fault with somebody else. And as to me, I am a very saucy girl; and were not this occasion, there would be some other, to shew this occasion.  You have heard me say, that this was always the case between We. You could not otherwise have known this was always the case between us. For when you was with We, you harmonized We both; and, indeed, I was always more afraid of you than of my mother. But then that awe is accompanied with love. Your reproofs, as I have always found, are so charmingly mild and instructive; so evidently calculated to improve, and not to provoke; that a generous temper must be amended by I have always found. But hear now, mind my good mamma, when you are not with We--You shall, I tell you, Nancy. I will have it so. Don't I know best, I won't be disobeyed. How can a daughter of spirits bear such language; such looks too with such language; and not have a longing mind to disobey?  Don't advise me, my dear, to subscribe to my mother's prohibition of correspondence with my dear. my mother has no reason for it. Nor would my mother of my mother own judgment have prohibited it. That odd old ambling soul your uncle, (whose visits are frequenter than ever,) instigated by your malicious and selfish brother and sister in this occasion. And That odd old ambling soul your uncle, (whose visits are frequenter than ever,) instigated by your malicious and selfish brother and sister in the occasion have only borrowed my mother's lips, at the distance That odd old ambling soul your uncle, (whose visits are frequenter than ever,) instigated by your malicious and selfish brother and sister in the occasion are from my dear, for a sort of speaking trumpet for That odd old ambling soul your uncle, (whose visits are frequenter than ever,) instigated by your malicious and selfish brother and sister in the occasion. The prohibition, once more I say, cannot come from my mother heart