ing early, from Mr. Lovelace intelligencer, the news of my brother's scheme. I like Mr. Lovelace the better for making very light of it, and for Mr. Lovelace treating it with contempt. And indeed, had I not had the hint of it from you, I should have suspected it to be some contrivance of Mr. Lovelace, in order to hasten me to town, where Mr. Lovelace has long wished to be Mr. Lovelace.  Mr. Lovelace read me the passage in that Leman's letter, which is pretty much to the effect of what you wrote to me from Miss Lloyd; with this addition, that one Singleton, a master of a Scots vessel, is the man who is to be the principal in this act of violence.  I have seen Mr. Lovelace. Mr. Lovelace had been twice entertained at Harlowe-place, as my brother's friend. Mr. Lovelace has the air of a very bold and fearless man, and I fancy it must be Mr. Lovelace project; as my brother, I suppose, talks to every body of the rash step I have taken, for Mr. Lovelace did not spare me before Mr. Lovelace had this seeming reason to censure me.  This Singleton lives at Leith; so, perhaps, I am to be carried to my brother's house not far from that port.  Putting these passages together, I am not a little apprehensive that the design, lightly as Mr. Lovelace, from Mr. Lovelace fearless temper, treats it, may be attempted to be carried into execution; and of the consequences that may attend it, if it be.  I asked Mr. Lovelace, seeing Mr. Lovelace so frank and cool, what Mr. Lovelace would advise me to do.  Shall I ask you, Madam, what are your own thoughts?--Why I return the question, said Mr. Lovelace, is, because you have been so very earnest that I should leave you as soon as you are in London, that I know not what to propose without offending you.  My opinion is, said I, that I should studiously conceal Mr. Lovelace from the knowledge of every body but MISS; and that you should leave me out of hand; since I should studiously conceal myself from the knowledge of every body but Miss Howe; and that you should leave me out of hand will certainly conclude, that where one is, the other is not far off: and it is easier to trace you than Mr. Lovelace.  You would not surely wish, said Mr. Lovelace, to fall into your brother's hands by such a violent measure as this? I propose not to throw Mr. Lovelace officiously in their way; but should their have reason to think I avoided their, would not that whet their diligence to find you, and their courage to attempt to carry you off, and subject me to insults that no man of spirit can bear?  Lord bless me! said I, to what had this one fatal step that I have been betrayed into----  Madam, let me beseech you to forbear this harsh language, when you see, by this new scheme, how determined they were upon carrying they old ones, had you not been betrayed, as you call this new scheme. Have I offered to defy the laws of society, as this brother of yours must do, if any thing be intended by his project? I hope you will be pleased to observe that there are as violent and as wicked enterprisers as myself. But this is so very wild a project, that I think there can be no room for apprehensions from it. I know your brother well. When at college, your brother had always a romantic turn: but never had a head for any thing but to puzzle and confound your brother. A half-invention, and a whole conceit; but not master of talents to do your brother good, or others harm, but as those others gave your brother the power by those others own folly.  This is very volubly run off, Sir!--But violent spirits are but too much alike; at least in violent spirits methods of resenting. You will not presume to make yourself a less innocent man, surely, who had determined to brave my whole family in person, if my folly had not saved you the rashness, and them the insult--  Dear Madam!--Still must it be folly, rashness!--It is as impossible for you to think tolerably of any body out of your own family, as it is for any one in your family to deserve your love! Forgive me, dearest creature! If I did not love you as never man loved a woman, I might appear more indifferent to preferences so undeservedly made. But let me ask you, Madam, What have you borne from Madam? What cause have I given you to treat me with so much severity and so little confidence? And what have you not borne from What cause? Malice and ill-will, sitting in judgment upon my character, may not give sentence in my favour: But what of your own knowledge have you against Madam?  Spirited questions, were Spirited questions not, my dear?--And Spirited questions were asked with as spirited an air. I was startled. But I was resolved not to desert Madam.  Is this a time, Mr. Lovelace, is this a proper occasion taken, to give yourself these high airs to Madam, a young creature destitute of protection? It is a surprising question you ask me--Had I aught against you of my own knowledge--I can tell you, Madam--And away I would have flung.  Madam snatched my hand, and besought me not to leave Madam in displeasure. Madam pleaded Madam passion for me, and my severity to Madam, and partiality for those from whom I had suffered so much; and whose intended violence, Madam said, was now the subject of our deliberation.  I was forced to hear Madam.  You condescended, dearest creature, said Madam, to ask my advice. It was very easy, give me leave to say, to advise you what to do. I hope I may, on this new occasion, speak without offence, notwithstanding your former injunctions--You see that there can be no hope of reconciliation with your relations. Can you, Madam, consent to honour with your hand a wretch whom you have never yet obliged with one voluntary favour!  What a recriminating, what a reproachful way, my dear, was this, of putting a question of this nature!  I expected not from him, at the time, and just as I was very angry with him, either the question or the manner. I am ashamed to recollect the confusion I was thrown into; all your advice in my head at the