lly--I am sure I looked very silly. my brother suffered me to pause, and look silly; waiting for me to say something: and at last (ashamed of my confusion, and aiming to make an excuse for it) I told my brother that I desired my brother would avoid such measures as might add to the uneasiness which it must be visible to my brother I had, when my brother reflected upon the irreconcilableness of my friends, and upon what might follow from this unaccountable project of my brother.  my brother promised to be governed by me in every thing. And again the wretch, instead of pressing my brother former question, asked me, If I forgave my brother for the humble suit my brother had made to me? What had I to do but to try for a palliation of my confusion, since it served me not?  I told my brother I had hopes it would not be long before Mr. Morden arrived; and doubted not that that gentleman would be the readier to engage in my favour, when Mr. Morden found that I made no other use of Mr. Morden (Mr. Lovelace's) assistance, than to free Mr. Morden from the addresses of a man so disagreeable to Mr. Morden as Mr. Solmes: I must therefore wish that every thing might remain as it was till I could hear from my cousin.  This, although teased by my cousin as I was, was not, you see, my dear, a denial. But my cousin must throw my cousin into a heat, rather than try to persuade; which any other man in my cousin situation, I should think, would have done; and this warmth obliged me to adhere to my seeming negative.  This was what my cousin said, with a vehemence that must harden any woman's mind, who had a spirit above being frighted into passiveness--  Good God! and will you, Madam, still resolve to show me that I am to hope for no share in your favour, while any the remotest prospect remains that you will be received by my bitterest enemies, at the price of my utter rejection?  This was what I returned, with warmth, and with a salving art too--You should have seen, Mr. Lovelace, how much my brother's violence can affect me: but you will be mistaken if you let loose yours upon me, with a thought of terrifying me into measures the contrary of which you have acquiesced with.  my brother only besought me to suffer my brother future actions to speak for my brother; and if I saw my brother worthy of any favour, that I would not let my brother be the only person within my knowledge who was not entitled to my consideration.  You refer to a future time, Mr. Lovelace, so do I, for the future proof of a merit you seem to think for the past time wanting: and justly you think so. And I was again going from my brother.  One word more my brother begged me to hear--my brother was determined studiously to avoid all mischief, and every step that might lead to mischief, let my brother's proceedings, short of a violence upon my person, be what they would: but if any attempt that should extend to that were to be made, would I have had my brother to be a quiet spectator of my being seized, or carried back, or on board, by This Singleton; or, in case of extremity, was my brother not permitted to stand up in my defence?  Stand up in my defence, my brother should be very miserable were there to be a call for that. But do you think I might not be safe and private in London? By your friend's description of the widow's house, I should think I might be safe there.  the widow's house, the widow replied, as described by the widow friend, being a back house within a front one, and looking to a garden, rather than to a street, had the appearance of privacy: but if, when there, it was not approved, it would be easy to find another more to my liking--though, as to the widow part, the method the widow would advise should be, to write to my uncle Harlowe, as one of my trustees, and wait the issue of it here at Mrs. Sorlings's, fearlessly directing it to be answered hither. To be afraid of little spirits was but to encourage insults, the widow said. The substance of the letter should