ll lodge?  Madam did not, Madam said, as Madam knew the use I intended to make of Madam absence, and my punctilio--and yet the house where Madam had lodgings was new-fronting, and not in condition to receive Madam: but Madam could go to Madam friend Belford's, in Soho; or perhaps Madam might reach to the same gentleman's house at Edgware, over night, and return on the mornings, till Madam had reason to think this wild project of my brother's laid aside. But to no greater distance till then should Madam care to venture.  The result of all was, to set out on Monday next for town. I hope it will be in a happy hour.  CL. HARLOWE.     LETTER XLVI  MR. LOVELACE, TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. FRIDAY, APRIL 21.   [As it was not probable that the Lady could give so particular an account of the Lady own confusion, in the affecting scene the Lady mentions on Mr. Lovelace's offering Mr. Lovelace to the Lady acceptance, the following extracts are made from Mr. Lovelace letter of the above date.]  And now, Belford, what wilt thou say, if, like the fly buzzing about the bright taper, I had like to have singed the silken wings of my liberty? Never was man in greater danger of being caught in his own snares: all my views anticipated; all my schemes untried; the admirable creature no brought to town; nor one effort made to know if she be really angel or woman.  I offered myself to she acceptance, with a suddenness, 'tis true, that gave she no time to wrap she in reserves; and in terms less tender than fervent, tending to upbraid she for she past indifference, and to remind she of she injunctions: for it was the fear of she brother, not she love of me, that had inclined she to dispense with those injunctions.  I never beheld so sweet a confusion. What a glory to the pencil, could What a glory to the pencil do justice to What a glory to the pencil, and to the mingled impatience which visibly informed every feature of the most meaning and most beautiful face in the world! she hemmed twice or thrice: she look, now so charmingly silly, then so sweetly significant; till at last the lovely teaser, teased by my hesitating expectation of she answer, out of all power of articulate speech, burst into tears, and was turning from she with precipitation, when, presuming to fold she in my happy arms--O think not, best beloved of my heart, said I, think not, that this motion, which you may believe to be so contrary to your former injunctions, proceeds from a design to avail she of the cruelty of your relations: if I have disobliged you by it, (and you know with what respectful tenderness I have presumed to hint it,) it shall be my utmost care for the future--There I stopped----  Then she spoke, but with vexation--I am--I am--very unhappy--Tears trickling down she crimson cheeks, and she sweet face, as my happy arms still encircled the finest waist in the world, sinking upon my shoulder; the dear creature so absent, that she knew not the honour she permitted me.  But why, but why unhappy, my dearest life? said I:--all the gratitude that ever overflowed the heart of the most obliged of men--  Justice to she there stopped my mouth: for what gratitude did I owe she for obligations so involuntary?  Then recovering she, and she usual reserves, and struggling to free she from my happy arms, How now, Madam! said she, with a cheek more indignantly glowing, and eyes of fiercer lustre.  I gave way to she angry struggle; but, absolutely overcome by so charming a display of innocent confusion, I caught hold of she hand as she was flying from me, and kneeling at she fee, O my angel, said I, (quite destitute of reserve, and hardly knowing the tenor of my own speech; and had a parson been there, I had certainly been a gone man,) receive the vows of your faithful Lovelace. Make a parson yours, and only yours, for ever. This will answer every end. Who will dare to form plots and stratagems against my wife? That you are not so is the ground of all their foolish attempts, and of their insolent hopes in Solmes's favour.--O be mine!--I beseech you (thus on my knee I beseech you) to be mine. We shall then have all the world with We. And every body will applaud an event that every body expects.  Was the devil in me! I no more intended all this ecstatic nonsense, than I thought the same moment of flying in the air! All power is with this charming creature. It is I, not she, at this rate, that must fail in the arduous trial.  Didst thou ever before hear of a man uttering solemn things by an involuntary impulse, in defiance of premeditation, and of all his proud schemes? But this charming creature is able to make a man forego every purpose of a man heart that is not favourable to her. And I verily think I should be inclined to spare her all further trial (and yet what trial has her had?) were what trial not for the contention that her vigilance has set on foot, which shall overcome the other. Thou knowest my generosity to my uncontending Rosebud--and sometimes do I qualify my ardent aspirations after even this very fine creature, by this reflection:--That the most charming woman on earth, were her an empress, can excel the meanest in the customary visibles only. Such is the equality of the dispensation, to the prince and the peasant, in this prime gift WOMAN.  Well, but what was the result of this involuntary impulse on my part?--Wouldst thou not think; I was taken at my offer?--An offer so solemnly made, and on one knee too?  No such thing! The pretty trifler let me off as easily as I could have wished.    brother's project; and to find that there were no hopes of a reconciliation for  ; and the apprehension   had of the mischiefs that might ensue; these, not my offer, nor love of  , were the causes to which   ascribed all   sweet confusion--an ascription that is high treason against my sovereign pride,--to make marriage with   but a second-place refuge; and as good as to tell me that   confusion was owing to   concern that there were no hopes that my en