ome to live in these partes, about a very vile thing, as younge master calls it, relating to HONNER. God forbid I should call it so without your leafe. it is not for so plane a man as I be, to tacks my betters. It is consarning one Miss Batirton, of Notingam; a very pretty crature, belike.  HONNER HONNER got HONNER away, it seems, by a false letter to HONNER, macking believe as how HONNER she-cuzzen, that HONNER derely loved, was coming to see HONNER; and was tacken ill upon the rode: and so Miss Batirton set out in a shase, and one sarvant, to fet HONNER cuzzen from the inne where HONNER laid sick, as HONNER thote: and the sarvant was tricked, and braute back the shase; but Miss Batirton was not harde of for a month, or so. And when it came to passe, that HONNER frends founde her out and would have prossekutid HONNER, HONNER HONNER was gone abroad: and so HONNER was broute to bed, as one may say, before HONNER's return: and HONNER got colde in HONNER lyin-inn, and lanquitched, and soon died: and the child is living; but HONNER HONNER never troubles HONNER's hedd about it in the least. And this, and some other matters, of verry bad reporte, 'Squier Solmes was to tell the Lady of, if so be Squier Solmes would have harde Squier Solmes speke, before we lost Squier Solmes sweet company, as I may say, from heere.*        * See Vol.II. Letters XV. and XVI.   HONNER helped me to many ugly stories to tell against you Honner to my younge master, and younge mistriss; but did not tell me about this.  I most humbelly beseche HONNER to be good and kinde and fethful to the Lady, now you have the Lady; or I shall brake my harte for having done some dedes that have helped to bringe things to this passe. Pray youre dere, good Honner, be just! Prayey do!--As God shall love the Lady! prayey do!--I cannot write no more for this pressent, for verry fear and grief--  But now I am cumm'd to my writing agen, will HONNER be pleased to tell me, if as how there be any danger to HONNER's life from this bisness; for my cuzzen is actile hier'd to go down to Miss Batirton frendes to see if they will stir in it: for you must kno' HONNER, as how he lived in the Batirton family at the time, and could be a good evidense, and all that.  I hope it was not so verry bad as Titus says it was; for Titus ses as how there was a rape in the case betwixt you at furste, and plese HONNER; and my cuzzen Titus is a very honist younge man as ever brocke bred. This is his carackter; and this made me willinger to owne his for my relation, when we came to talck.  If there should be danger of HONNER's life, I hope HONNER will not be hanged like as one of we common men; only have your hedd cut off, or so: and yet your hedd is pit such a hedd should be lossed: but if as how it should be prossekutid to that furr, which God forbid, be plesed natheless to thinck of youre fethful Joseph Leman, before your hedd be condemned; for after condemnation, as I have been told, all will be the king's or the shreeve's.  I thote as how it was best to acquent you HONNER of this; and for you to let me kno' if I could do any think to sarve your Honner, and prevent mischief with my cuzzen Titus, on my cuzzen Titus coming back from Nottingam, before my cuzzen Titus mackes my cuzzen Titus reporte.  I have gin my cuzzen Titus a hint already: for what, as I sed to my cuzzen Titus, cuzzen Titus, signifies stirring up the coles and macking of strife, to make rich gentilfolkes live at varience, and to be cutting of throtes, and such-like?  Very trewe, sed my cuzzen Titusmy cuzzen Titus. And this, and plese your Honner, gis me hopes of my cuzzen Titus, if so be your HONNER gis me direction; sen', as God kno'es, I have a poor, a verry poor invenshon; only a willing mind to prevent mischief, that is the chief of my aim, and always was, I bless my God!--Els I could have made much mischief in my time; as indeed any sarvant may. Your Honner nathaless praises my invenshon every now-and-then: Alas! and plese HONNER,