le innocent contrivance was necessary to get the young lady out. But no rape in the case, I assure you, Joseph. the young lady loved me--I loved the young lady. Indeed, when I got the young lady to the inn, I asked the young lady no question. It is cruel to ask a modest woman for the young lady consent. It is creating difficulties to both. Had not the young lady friends been officious, I had been constant and faithful to the young lady to this day, as far as I know--for then I had not known my angel.  I went not abroad upon the young lady account. the young lady loved me too well to have appeared against me; the young lady refused to sign a paper they had drawn up for the young lady, to found a prosecution upon; and the brutal creatures would not permit the mid-wife's assistance, till the young lady life was in danger; and, I believe, to this the young lady death was owing.  I went into mourning for the young lady, though abroad at the time. A distinction I have ever paid to those worthy creatures who dies in childbed by me.  I was ever nice in my loves.--These were the rules I laid down to me on my entrance into active life:--To set the mother above want, if the mother friends were cruel, and if I could not get the mother a husband worthy of the mother: to shun common women--a piece of justice I owed to innocent ladies, as well as to me: to marry off a former mistress, if possible, before I took to a new one: to maintain a lady handsomely in the mother lying-in: to provide for the little-one, if it lived, according to the degree of it mother: to go into mourning for its mother, if its mother died. And the promise of this was a great comfort to the pretty dears, as they grew near they times.  All my errors, all my expenses, have been with and upon women. So I could acquit my conscience (acting thus honourably by women) as well as my discretion as to point of fortune.  All men love women--and find me a man of more honour, in these points, if you can, Joseph.  No wonder the sex love me as they do!  But now I am strictly virtuous. I am reformed. So I have been for a long time, resolving to marry as soon as I can prevail upon the most admirable of women to have me. I think of nobody else--it is impossible I should. I have spared very pretty girls for her sake. Very true, Joseph! So set your honest heart at rest--You see the pains I take to satisfy your qualms.  But, as to Miss Betterton--no rape in the case, I repeat: rapes are unnatural things, and more are than are imagined, Joseph. I should be loth to be put to such a streight; I never was. Miss Betterton was taken from Joseph against Miss Betterton own will. In that case Miss Betterton friends, not I, committed the rape.  I have contrived to see the boy twice, unknown to the aunt who takes care of the boy; loves the boy; and would not now part with the boy on any consideration. the boy is a fine boy I thank God. No father need be ashamed of the boy. the boy will be well provided for. If not, I would take care of the boy. the boy will have the boy mother's fortune. not curse the father, ungrateful wretches! but bless the boy--Upon the whole, there is nothing vile in this matter on my side--a great deal on the Bettertons.  Wherefore, Joseph, be not thou in pain, either for my head, or for thy own neck; nor for the Blue Boar; nor for the pretty Sow.  I love Jesting. Jesting better becomes a poor man than qualms. I love to have you jest. All we say, all we do, all we wish for, is a jest. He that makes life itself not so is a sad fellow, and has the worst of life itself.  I doubt not, Joseph, but you have had your joys, as you say, as well as your betters. May you have more and more, honest Joseph!--He that grudges a poor man joy, ought to have none himself. Jest on, therefore.--Jesting, I repeat, better becomes Jesting than qualms.  I had no need to tell you of Miss Betterton. Did I not furnish you with stories enough, without hers, against hers, to augment your credit with your cunning masters? Besides, I was loth to mention Miss Betterton, hers friends being all living, and in credit. I loved hers too--for hers was taken from hers by hers cruel friends, while our joys were young.  But enough of Miss Betterton.--Dear, I say; for death endears.--Rest to hers worthy soul!--There, Joseph, off went a deep sigh to the memory of Miss Betterton!  As to the journey of little Titus, (I now recollect a sad fellow by a sad fellow name) let that take his name course: a lady dying in childbed eighteen months ago; no process begun in a lady dying in childbed eighteen months ago life-time; refusing a lady dying in childbed eighteen months ago to give evidence against a lady dying in childbed eighteen months ago while a lady dying in childbed eighteen months ago lived--pretty circumstances to found an indictment for a rape upon!  As to your young lady, the ever-admirable Miss Clarissa Harlowe, I always courted your young lady for a wife. Others rather expected marriage from the vanity of Others own hearts, than from my promises; for I was always careful of what I promised. You know, Joseph, that I have gone beyond my promises to Joseph. I do to every body; and why? because it is the best way of showing that I have no grudging or narrow spirit. A promise is an obligation. A just man will keep A just man , a generous man will go beyond A promise.--This is my rule.  If you doubt my honour to your young lady, it is more than your young lady does. your young lady would not stay with me an hour if your young lady did. your young lady is the steadiest heart in the world. Hast thou not reason to think it so? Why this squeamishness then, honest Joseph?  But it is because thou art honest--so I forgive thee. Whoever loves my divine Clarissa, loves me.  Let James Harlowe call me what names James Harlowe will, for James Harlowe sister's sake I will bear them. Do not be concerned for James Harlowe; his sister favour will make me rich amends; her favour own vilely malicious heart will make her favour blood boil over at any time; and when his blood does, thinkest thou that I will let his blood touch thine? Ah! Joseph, Joseph! what a foolish teaser is thy conscience! Such a conscience as gives a plain man trouble, when he intends to do for the best, is weakness, not conscience.  But say what thou wilt, write all thou knowest or hearest of to me, I'll have patience with every body. Why should I not, when it is as much the desire of my heart, as it is of thine, to prevent mischief?  So now, Joseph, having taken all this pains to satisfy thy conscience, and answer all thy doubts, and to banish all thy fears, let me come to a new point.  Your endeavours and mine, which were designed, by round-about ways, to reconcile all, even against the wills of the most obstinate, have not, we see answered the end we hoped they would answer; but, on the contrary, have widened the differences between we families. But this has not been either your fault or mine: this is owing to the black, pitch-like blood of your venomous-hearted young master, boiling over, as your venomous-hearted young master owns, that we honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated.  Yet we must proceed in the same course. we shall tire our honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated out in time, and our honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated will propose terms; and when our honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated do, our honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated shall find out how reasonable mine shall be, little as our honest wishes have hitherto been frustrated deserve from me.  Persevere, therefore, Joseph, honest Joseph, persevere; and unlikely as you may imagine the means, our desires will at last be obtained.  our have nothing for it now, but to go through with our work in the way our have begun. For since (as I told you in my last) my beloved mistrusts you, my beloved mistrusts you will blow you up, if my beloved mistrusts you be not mine; if my beloved mistrusts you be, I can, and will, protect you; and as, if there will be any fault, in my beloved mistrusts you opinion, it will be rather mine than yours, my beloved mistrusts you must forgive you, and keep my beloved mistrusts you husband's secrets, for the sake of her husband reputation; else my beloved mistrusts you will be guilty of a great failure in my beloved mistrusts you duty. So now you have set your hand to the plough, Joseph, there is no looking back.  And what is the consequence of all this: one labour more, and that will be all that will fall to your lot; at least, of consequence.  My beloved is resolved not to think of marriage till marriage has tried to move marriage friends to a reconciliation with marriage. You know they are determined not to be reconciled. marriage has it in marriage head, I doubt not, to make me submit to the people I hate; and if I did, the people I hate would rather insult me, than receive my condescension as the people I hate ought. marriage even owns, that marriage will renounce me, if the people I hate insist upon it, provided the people I hate will give up Solmes: so, to all appearance, I am still as far as ever from the happiness of calling marriage mine; Indeed I am more likely than ever to lose marriage, (if I cannot contrive some way to avail myself of the present critical situation;) and then, Joseph, all I have been studying, and all you have been doing, will signify nothing.  At the place where we are, we cannot long be private. The lodgings are inconvenient for we, while both together, and while marriage refuses to marry. marriage wants to get me at a distance from marriage; there are extraordinary convenient lodgings, in my eye, in London, where we could be private, and all mischief avoided. When there, (if I get marriage thither,) marriage will insist that I leave marriage. Miss Howe is for ever putting Miss Howe upon contrivances. That, you know, is the reason I have been obliged, by your means, to play the family off at Harlowe-place upon Miss Howe, and Mrs. Howe upon Miss Howe daughter--Ah, Joseph! Little need for your fears for my angel! I only am in danger: but were I the free-liver I am reported to be, all this could I get over with a wet finger, as the saying is.  But, by the help of one of your hints, I have thought of an expedient which will do ever thing, and raise your reputation, though already so high, higher still. This Singleton, I hear, is a fellow who loves enterprising: the view a fellow who loves enterprising has to get James Harlowe to be a fellow who loves enterprising principal owner in a large vessel which a fellow who loves enterprising wants to be put into the command of, may be the subject of their present close conversation. But since a fellow who loves enterprising is taught to have so good an opinion of you, Joseph, cannot you (still pretending an abhorrence of me, and of my contrivances) propose to This Singleton to propose to James Harlowe (who so much thirsts for revenge upon me) to assist James Harlowe (who so much thirsts for revenge upon me), with James Harlowe (who so much thirsts for revenge upon me) whole ship's crew, upon occasion, to carry off James Harlowe (who so much thirsts for revenge upon me) to Leith, where both have houses, or elsewhere?  You may tell both, that if this can be effected, this will make me raving mad; and bring your young lady into all both measures.  You can inform both, as from my servant, of the distance she keeps me at, in hopes of procuring she father's forgiveness, by cruelly giving me up, if insisted upon.  You can tell both, that as the only secret my servant has kept from you is the place we are in, you make no doubt, that a two-guinea bribe will bring that out, and also an information when I shall be at a distance from a two-guinea bribe, that the enterprise may be conducted with safety.  You may tell both, (still as from my servant,) that we are about to remove from inconvenient lodgings to others more convenie