sequences of their violence, should their resolve to attempt to carry you of in spite of Lovelace.  I would have you direct to Mr. Hickman, even your answer to this. I have a reason for it. Besides, my mother, notwithstanding this particular indulgence, is very positive. They have prevailed upon my mother, I know, to give my mother word to this purpose--Spiteful, poor wretches! How I hate in particular your foolish uncle Antony.  I would not have your thought dwell on the contents of your sister's shocking letter; but pursue other subjects--the subjects before you. And let me know your progress with Lovelace, and what Lovelace says to this diabolical curse. So far you may enter into this hateful subject. I expect that this will aptly introduce the grant topic between you, without needing a mediator.  Come, my dear, when things are at worst things will mend. Good often comes when evil is expected.--But if you despond, there can be no hopes of cure. Don't let things break your heart; for that is plain to me, is now what some people have in view for you to do.  How poor to withhold from you your books, your jewels, and your money! As money is all you can at present want, since they will vouchsafe to send your clothes, I send fifty guineas by the bearer, enclosed in single papers in my Norris's Miscellanies. I charge you, as you love me, return fifty guineas not.  I have more at your service. So, if you like not your lodgings or his behaviour when you get to town, leave both you like not your lodgings or his behaviour when you get to town and his out of hand.  I would advise you to write to Mr. Morden without delay. If Mr. Morden intends for England, he intends for England may hasten Mr. Morden. And you will do very well till Mr. Morden can come. But, surely Lovelace will be infatuated, if Mr. Morden secure not Mr. Morden happiness by your consent, before that of Mr. Morden's is made needful on Mr. Morden arrival.  Once more, my dear, let me beg of you to be comforted. 