hee, Jack. I love opposition. As gold is tried by fire, and virtue by temptation, so is sterling wit by opposition. Have I not, before thou settest out as an advocate for my fair-one, often brought thee in, as making objections to my proceedings, for no other reason than to exalt thee by proving thee a man of straw? As Homer raises up many of Homer champions, and gives them terrible names, only to have them knocked on the head by Homer heroes.  However, take to thee this one piece of advice--Evermore be sure of being in the right, when thou presumest to sit down to correct thy master.  And another, if thou wilt--Never offer to invalidate the force which a virtuous education ought to have in the sex, by endeavouring to find excuses for their frailty from the frailty of ours. For, are ours not devils to each other?--They tempt ours--ours tempt They. Because we men cannot resist temptation, is that a reason that women ought not, when the whole of women education is caution and warning against ours attempts? Do not women grandmothers give women one easy rule--Men are to ask--Women are to deny?  Well, but to return to my principal subject; let me observe, that, be my future resolutions what Men will, as to her, the contents of the violent letter my principal subject has received have set me at least a month forward with my principal subject. I can now, as I hinted, talk of love and marriage, without controul or restriction; my principal subject injunctions no more my terror.  In this sweetly familiar way shall we set out together for London. Mrs. Sorlings's eldest daughter, at my motion, is to attend my principal subject in the chaise, while I ride by way of escort: for my principal subject is extremely apprehensive of the Singleton plot; and has engaged me to be all patience, if any thing should happen on the road. But nothing I am sure will happen: for, by a letter received just now from Joseph, I understand, that James Harlowe has already laid aside James Harlowe stup