t overcome thee now, I never will again attempt to conquer thee.  The dear creature continues extremely low and dejected. Tender blossom! how unfit to contend with the rude and ruffling winds of passion, and haughty and insolent control!--Never till now from under the wing (it is not enough to say of indulging, but) of admiring parents; the mother's bosom only fit to receive this charming flower!  This was the reflection, that, with mingled compassion, and augmented love, arose to my mind, when I beheld the charmer reposing the charmer lovely face upon the bosom of the widow Sorlings, from a recovered fit, as I entered soon after the charmer had received the charmer execrable sister's letter. How lovely in the charmer tears!--And as I entered, the charmer uplifted face significantly bespeaking my protection, as I thought. And can I be a villain to such an angel!--I hope not--But why, Belford, why, once more, puttest thou me in mind, that the charmer may be overcome? And why is the charmer own reliance on my honour so late and so reluctantly shown?  But, after all, so low, so dejected, continues the charmer to be, that I am terribly afraid I shall have a vapourish wife, if I do marry. I should then be doubly undone. Not that I shall be much at home with the charmer, perhaps, after the first fortnight, or so. But when a man has been ranging, like the painful bee, from flower to flower, perhaps for a month together, and the thoughts of home and a wife begin to have the thoughts of home and a wife charms with a man, to be received by a Niobe, who, like a wounded vine, weeps a wife vitals away, while a wife but involuntary curls about a man; how shall I be able to bear that?  May Heaven restore my charmer to health and spirits, I hourly pray--that a man may see whether a wife can love any body but a wife father and mother! In their power, I am confident, it will be, at any time, to make a wife husband joyless; and that, as I hate their so heartily, is a shocking thing to